WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.110 --> 00:00:03.790
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER:
OK, good morning.

00:00:03.790 --> 00:00:08.950
So, I wanted to talk today about
Behavioral Finance or

00:00:08.950 --> 00:00:12.410
about Psychology and Finance.

00:00:12.410 --> 00:00:17.250
This is a longstanding
interest of mine.

00:00:17.250 --> 00:00:21.190
I've been involved with
it for over 20 years.

00:00:21.190 --> 00:00:27.080
It's not really emphasized in
your textbook, Fabozzi and his

00:00:27.080 --> 00:00:32.000
co-authors talk about a lot of
things in the financial world,

00:00:32.000 --> 00:00:34.750
but not about the underlying
human behavior.

00:00:37.280 --> 00:00:41.670
Behavioral Finance, or
Behavioral Economics more

00:00:41.670 --> 00:00:45.770
broadly, is a kind of revolution
that has occurred

00:00:45.770 --> 00:00:53.260
in finance and economics over
the last 20 or 30 years.

00:00:53.260 --> 00:00:56.740
And it remains somewhat
controversial.

00:00:56.740 --> 00:01:00.760
I don't quite fully understand
why it is that people polarize

00:01:00.760 --> 00:01:03.630
as much as they do, but some
people don't like this.

00:01:07.980 --> 00:01:11.100
We're coming along to be
the majority, I think.

00:01:11.100 --> 00:01:13.800
People are now regarding
Behavioral Finance as an

00:01:13.800 --> 00:01:15.350
important element of finance.

00:01:18.470 --> 00:01:24.240
But the real problem is that
people are complex and our

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:28.750
financial institutions, as I've
emphasized, are designed

00:01:28.750 --> 00:01:32.490
for real people and their
functioning depends on the

00:01:32.490 --> 00:01:37.880
behavior of real people.

00:01:37.880 --> 00:01:40.520
And it's not as simple.

00:01:40.520 --> 00:01:45.630
You know, another revolution
that's occurring parallel, of

00:01:45.630 --> 00:01:50.430
bigger significance, is a
revolution in neuroscience

00:01:50.430 --> 00:01:52.420
about the human brain.

00:01:52.420 --> 00:01:57.760
And the human brain is a
very complicated organ.

00:02:02.790 --> 00:02:05.650
Economists have liked to
invoke the principle of

00:02:05.650 --> 00:02:10.700
rationality as an underlying
component of their theory, and

00:02:10.700 --> 00:02:15.900
that has been useful, but it's
of limited use, because people

00:02:15.900 --> 00:02:17.000
aren't rational.

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:18.810
They are often rational,
they're

00:02:18.810 --> 00:02:21.240
not completely rational.

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:24.210
And very often, people
behave stupidly.

00:02:24.210 --> 00:02:26.190
I'll put it that way.

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:31.270
That includes everyone,
including me, because we're

00:02:31.270 --> 00:02:32.520
human and we have limits.

00:02:38.770 --> 00:02:42.800
One thing about the human
species is that we are aware

00:02:42.800 --> 00:02:45.560
of other people's weaknesses
and have an

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:48.330
impulse to exploit them.

00:02:48.330 --> 00:02:52.090
So when you see other people
behaving stupidly, sometimes

00:02:52.090 --> 00:02:55.970
you think, maybe I can turn
this to my advantage.

00:02:55.970 --> 00:02:57.490
OK?

00:02:57.490 --> 00:03:03.490
And that becomes a problem.

00:03:03.490 --> 00:03:08.130
The history of humankind is a
history of exploitation of one

00:03:08.130 --> 00:03:11.380
person by another.

00:03:11.380 --> 00:03:13.220
Not entirely, but I'm saying
it has that as

00:03:13.220 --> 00:03:15.960
an important element.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:18.270
So, I'm going to talk about
these human failings.

00:03:18.270 --> 00:03:21.650
It's not to say that people are
stupid, I'm just saying

00:03:21.650 --> 00:03:24.130
they're people, and we're
all imperfect.

00:03:24.130 --> 00:03:28.120
We're smart in some dimensions
and we can be very smart, but

00:03:28.120 --> 00:03:32.340
we can also make important
mistakes.

00:03:32.340 --> 00:03:38.450
But before I start, I wanted
to try to put this into a

00:03:38.450 --> 00:03:40.150
perspective.

00:03:40.150 --> 00:03:45.800
Maybe, I'll return to this at
the end of the lecture, but I

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:47.820
wanted to start out
on an upbeat note.

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:50.640
I'm going to talk about all
kinds of human errors, but I

00:03:50.640 --> 00:03:57.310
wanted to start on an upbeat
note that the business world

00:03:57.310 --> 00:04:01.800
generally doesn't exploit
people terribly.

00:04:01.800 --> 00:04:11.880
I believe that very
characteristically successful

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:18.000
businesses in finance and
elsewhere consider their

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:23.020
long-term advantage and the
reputation they have. So,

00:04:23.020 --> 00:04:26.630
doing something that is
blatantly exploitative of

00:04:26.630 --> 00:04:30.240
human weaknesses will
work against

00:04:30.240 --> 00:04:31.655
their long-term advantage.

00:04:36.400 --> 00:04:39.570
You'll see a lot of human
failings, but we don't see

00:04:39.570 --> 00:04:45.210
people cashing in on them
as often as you'd think.

00:04:45.210 --> 00:04:48.900
And beyond that, I want to
emphasize also that another

00:04:48.900 --> 00:04:53.690
aspect of human behavior
is morality.

00:04:53.690 --> 00:04:58.550
Evolutionary biologists think
that this evolved along with

00:04:58.550 --> 00:05:02.840
our other traits, that we have
an impulse to be moral.

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:06.920
And so, in the long run, you
might not really gain so much

00:05:06.920 --> 00:05:11.010
satisfaction from exploiting
other people's mistakes.

00:05:11.010 --> 00:05:17.200
And so, you don't necessarily
do that.

00:05:17.200 --> 00:05:21.130
So, that's why we have a lot of
weaknesses outlined and we

00:05:21.130 --> 00:05:25.960
won't see significant or serious
exploitation of them

00:05:25.960 --> 00:05:27.870
as characteristic.

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:31.660
Now as you know, I have chapters
from my forthcoming

00:05:31.660 --> 00:05:34.550
book assigned for this course.

00:05:34.550 --> 00:05:39.170
And I looked back on what I put
up for you to read and I

00:05:39.170 --> 00:05:42.070
keep thinking, gee, this
really wasn't ready.

00:05:42.070 --> 00:05:46.820
So, I had a chapter for this
section of the reading list

00:05:46.820 --> 00:05:49.420
about Behavioral Finance.

00:05:49.420 --> 00:05:52.050
And I thought, I didn't
really get it right.

00:05:52.050 --> 00:05:54.870
I know what I was trying to
say, but maybe I should --

00:05:54.870 --> 00:05:58.950
what I start out in that chapter
is talking about Adam

00:05:58.950 --> 00:06:05.660
Smith and his book The Theory
of Moral Sentiments.

00:06:05.660 --> 00:06:12.390
Now just to remind you, Adam
Smith was a professor in

00:06:12.390 --> 00:06:17.530
Scotland in 1759.

00:06:17.530 --> 00:06:20.470
He was a professor of moral
philosophy, because there were

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:24.800
no professors of economics
in those days.

00:06:24.800 --> 00:06:27.390
And he wrote in 1759 --

00:06:27.390 --> 00:06:29.403
Maybe I should write some
of this on the board. --

00:06:36.530 --> 00:06:39.870
He's probably the most important
figure in the

00:06:39.870 --> 00:06:43.060
history of economic thought.

00:06:43.060 --> 00:06:50.310
So, in 1759 he wrote his The
Theory of Moral Sentiments.

00:06:50.310 --> 00:06:56.480
And in 1776, he wrote the
more famous book,

00:06:56.480 --> 00:06:57.730
The Wealth of Nations.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:04.245
So, this is The Theory
of Moral Sentiment.

00:07:06.840 --> 00:07:14.610
The Wealth of Nations is
considered the first real

00:07:14.610 --> 00:07:17.500
treatise on economics and
it's a wonderful book.

00:07:17.500 --> 00:07:19.180
And it's still very
readable today.

00:07:22.280 --> 00:07:24.390
His The Theory of Moral
Sentiments is

00:07:24.390 --> 00:07:26.340
not so widely read.

00:07:26.340 --> 00:07:30.910
But it's not really economics,
it's a book about psychology

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:33.330
and morality.

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:39.130
I find it very good, even
250 years later.

00:07:39.130 --> 00:07:42.410
He went through many editions on
this book, because maybe he

00:07:42.410 --> 00:07:44.570
thought it was his most
important work.

00:07:44.570 --> 00:07:49.090
But the book starts out about
selfishness and altruism.

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:53.450
And the real question, which he
thinks defines economics,

00:07:53.450 --> 00:07:57.000
is, are people really
completely selfish?

00:07:57.000 --> 00:08:00.990
Sometimes it seems that way,
that their presumed

00:08:00.990 --> 00:08:03.010
benevolence is just an artifice

00:08:03.010 --> 00:08:04.260
for their own benefit.

00:08:07.800 --> 00:08:10.410
But he wonders, how does an
economy work if everyone is

00:08:10.410 --> 00:08:11.540
totally selfish?

00:08:11.540 --> 00:08:14.470
And he ends up concluding
that they're not.

00:08:14.470 --> 00:08:15.590
I thought it was very
interesting,

00:08:15.590 --> 00:08:17.085
the way he put it.

00:08:17.085 --> 00:08:20.070
The thing he emphasized right
at the beginning of the book

00:08:20.070 --> 00:08:25.740
is that people inherently
love praise.

00:08:25.740 --> 00:08:29.840
We crave the approval
of other people.

00:08:29.840 --> 00:08:35.710
And so, praise is a fundamental
human desire.

00:08:35.710 --> 00:08:38.750
But then he reflected on it and
he said, do people really

00:08:38.750 --> 00:08:45.100
want praise itself or is it
something else that they want?

00:08:45.100 --> 00:08:45.880
Well, think of it this way.

00:08:45.880 --> 00:08:49.560
Suppose people made a big
mistake and thought that you

00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:52.650
had accomplished something,
but there was a mix up.

00:08:52.650 --> 00:08:54.220
You know, it was really
somebody else

00:08:54.220 --> 00:08:55.470
who did it, not you.

00:08:55.470 --> 00:08:57.800
And it's just a complete
mistake.

00:08:57.800 --> 00:09:00.660
You had nothing to do with it,
but you find lots of people

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:02.150
praising you.

00:09:02.150 --> 00:09:05.640
Would that really
be pleasurable?

00:09:05.640 --> 00:09:08.730
And suppose you even know that
they'll never find out that I

00:09:08.730 --> 00:09:10.100
didn't do it.

00:09:10.100 --> 00:09:12.510
Well, Smith said, it
probably isn't.

00:09:12.510 --> 00:09:13.720
Think about it.

00:09:13.720 --> 00:09:16.990
You internally are thinking, I'm
getting all this praise,

00:09:16.990 --> 00:09:19.870
but I know I don't deserve it.

00:09:19.870 --> 00:09:22.060
So, I don't enjoy it.

00:09:22.060 --> 00:09:25.170
And then he went on to say that,
especially among people

00:09:25.170 --> 00:09:28.720
who are more mature, he says
more mature people --

00:09:28.720 --> 00:09:30.830
not everyone makes this step.

00:09:30.830 --> 00:09:35.550
But he says, adults, normal,
mature adults, make a

00:09:35.550 --> 00:09:39.960
transition from a desire for
praise to a desire for

00:09:39.960 --> 00:09:42.480
praise-worthiness.

00:09:42.480 --> 00:09:46.810
I want to know that I am the
kind of person who will be

00:09:46.810 --> 00:09:50.480
praised and I don't need
to get the praise.

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:53.850
And he said, it's that tendency
ultimately, which

00:09:53.850 --> 00:09:56.860
makes an economy work,
that people don't

00:09:56.860 --> 00:10:00.080
care just about praise.

00:10:00.080 --> 00:10:02.650
He gives an example
of mathematicians.

00:10:02.650 --> 00:10:05.820
And he said he's known many
mathematicians in his life and

00:10:05.820 --> 00:10:08.390
he finds that they're
almost all obscure.

00:10:08.390 --> 00:10:10.760
The public doesn't know
about mathematicians.

00:10:10.760 --> 00:10:14.060
They couldn't explain to the
public what they do.

00:10:14.060 --> 00:10:18.730
And they don't seem to care at
all, because they know the

00:10:18.730 --> 00:10:21.310
public doesn't appreciate
mathematics.

00:10:21.310 --> 00:10:25.080
And so, there's a few
mathematician friends who

00:10:25.080 --> 00:10:28.520
understand what they do
and may praise them.

00:10:28.520 --> 00:10:31.190
But ultimately, a mathematician
can sometimes do

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:35.730
the work completely unknown.

00:10:35.730 --> 00:10:43.850
And it's the praise-worthiness
that drives these people.

00:10:43.850 --> 00:10:46.850
You may think I'm being too
idealistic, when I say this,

00:10:46.850 --> 00:10:50.750
but I think that the finance
profession --

00:10:50.750 --> 00:10:53.860
this is what I was trying
to say in that chapter.

00:10:53.860 --> 00:10:58.940
That the finance profession,
like other mature professions,

00:10:58.940 --> 00:11:01.140
is really dominated --

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:02.840
although there's a lot of funny
things that happen.

00:11:02.840 --> 00:11:07.610
It is really dominated by people
who have reached this

00:11:07.610 --> 00:11:10.040
desire for praise-worthiness.

00:11:10.040 --> 00:11:13.150
And so, you're not going to
exploit people extravagantly.

00:11:13.150 --> 00:11:15.100
Just because, why
would I do that?

00:11:15.100 --> 00:11:16.010
This is not a good thing.

00:11:16.010 --> 00:11:19.420
I wouldn't feel good about it.

00:11:19.420 --> 00:11:20.810
Well, some people will.

00:11:20.810 --> 00:11:25.470
Now, I wanted to also mention,
not everyone reaches this

00:11:25.470 --> 00:11:31.570
mature state that Adam
Smith describes.

00:11:31.570 --> 00:11:34.310
And that's one of the
complexities of human society.

00:11:34.310 --> 00:11:38.470
And I think that the finance
profession has a problem with

00:11:38.470 --> 00:11:39.910
other kinds of people.

00:11:39.910 --> 00:11:42.620
Now there's a whole branch of
psychology called Personality

00:11:42.620 --> 00:11:46.820
Psychology that categorizes
people by their personality.

00:11:46.820 --> 00:11:48.890
And we're not all the same.

00:11:48.890 --> 00:11:54.890
And in our society, we have
many different kinds of

00:11:54.890 --> 00:11:57.180
personalities.

00:11:57.180 --> 00:12:01.940
A successful society promotes
people up who have the

00:12:01.940 --> 00:12:03.930
praise-worthiness desire.

00:12:03.930 --> 00:12:06.440
We try to recognize them and
we try to put people of

00:12:06.440 --> 00:12:10.700
character into important
positions, with

00:12:10.700 --> 00:12:12.320
not complete success.

00:12:12.320 --> 00:12:14.380
But I wanted to just briefly
talk about --

00:12:14.380 --> 00:12:17.650
this is a lecture
on psychology.

00:12:17.650 --> 00:12:22.050
I wanted to talk about other
personality types.

00:12:22.050 --> 00:12:26.620
And I was going to use a book
called The Diagnostic and

00:12:26.620 --> 00:12:32.480
Statistical Manual Edition IV
published by the American

00:12:32.480 --> 00:12:34.620
Psychiatric Association.

00:12:34.620 --> 00:12:39.310
They're coming out with a
fifth edition in 2014.

00:12:39.310 --> 00:12:43.190
DSM-IV is kind of a household
word around my house, because

00:12:43.190 --> 00:12:48.830
my wife is a psychologist.
DSM-IV is actually

00:12:48.830 --> 00:12:51.970
controversial among
psychiatrists, because it's

00:12:51.970 --> 00:12:54.010
too cut and dry for
some of them.

00:12:54.010 --> 00:12:58.720
What it tries to do is, identify
mental illnesses and

00:12:58.720 --> 00:13:03.190
personality types in a
quantifiable, reproducible

00:13:03.190 --> 00:13:07.950
way, so that we can define who
has this mental illness or who

00:13:07.950 --> 00:13:11.940
has this personality type.

00:13:11.940 --> 00:13:15.240
And so, it gives you checklists
and it says, the

00:13:15.240 --> 00:13:20.390
patient must have exhibited at
least three of the following

00:13:20.390 --> 00:13:21.890
five behaviors.

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:25.100
And then, there will be another
checklist. And so, you

00:13:25.100 --> 00:13:28.430
keep score and you can actually

00:13:28.430 --> 00:13:30.900
diagnosis personality disorders.

00:13:30.900 --> 00:13:32.100
I'm just going to mention
one of the

00:13:32.100 --> 00:13:35.240
many personality disorders.

00:13:35.240 --> 00:13:38.890
One of them is called
APD, called

00:13:38.890 --> 00:13:42.830
Antisocial Personality Disorder.

00:13:42.830 --> 00:13:44.310
And so they have checklists,
but just to

00:13:44.310 --> 00:13:45.860
give you a sense --

00:13:45.860 --> 00:13:52.070
oh, and the Antisocial
Personality Disorder is called

00:13:52.070 --> 00:13:58.080
psychopathy, or one kind
of APD is psychopathy.

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:01.590
Another one is called
sociopathy and --

00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:02.190
I don't know.

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:04.300
There's a huge literature
on these.

00:14:04.300 --> 00:14:11.980
But according to DSM-IV, 3% of
the male population in the

00:14:11.980 --> 00:14:20.230
world is APD, and 1% of
the female population.

00:14:20.230 --> 00:14:24.800
A simple definition
for APD is a jerk.

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:32.380
There are more male jerks than
female jerks, apparently,

00:14:32.380 --> 00:14:34.480
according to their --

00:14:34.480 --> 00:14:36.540
this is all quantifiable
and done.

00:14:36.540 --> 00:14:41.740
But what is an Antisocial
Personality Disorder?

00:14:41.740 --> 00:14:44.370
It has the following
characteristics: lack of

00:14:44.370 --> 00:14:52.550
remorse, frequent lying, lack of
empathy, superficial charm,

00:14:52.550 --> 00:14:58.280
shallow emotions, distorted
sense of self, constant search

00:14:58.280 --> 00:14:59.420
for new sensations.

00:14:59.420 --> 00:15:01.020
Have you met someone
like that?

00:15:01.020 --> 00:15:07.430
You probably have, because
that's 3% of the population.

00:15:07.430 --> 00:15:09.660
I'm not anti-male, when I point
out there are three

00:15:09.660 --> 00:15:13.000
times as many jerks among
males as females.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:16.290
Females have characteristically
different

00:15:16.290 --> 00:15:17.620
personality disorders.

00:15:17.620 --> 00:15:21.640
And you can look down the list.
It's much more than 3%

00:15:21.640 --> 00:15:23.450
of the population that
would be diagnosed

00:15:23.450 --> 00:15:25.240
with one or the other.

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:30.370
So, you know, an APD person
is manipulative, feigns

00:15:30.370 --> 00:15:34.590
affectionate or warm feelings,
but doesn't feel them, and is

00:15:34.590 --> 00:15:35.940
trying to deceive you.

00:15:39.010 --> 00:15:42.700
Once a student came to my office
and asked to sign up as

00:15:42.700 --> 00:15:44.640
my research assistant.

00:15:44.640 --> 00:15:46.510
I was talking and I thought,
well, maybe.

00:15:46.510 --> 00:15:48.000
I said come back
and talk to me.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:50.570
Later on, I read about him
in the Yale Daily News.

00:15:50.570 --> 00:15:52.970
He was an impostor student.

00:15:52.970 --> 00:15:55.180
He was not a Yale student.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:57.780
And he had been around to other
university campuses.

00:15:57.780 --> 00:16:00.580
He was an impostor at like
three different campuses.

00:16:00.580 --> 00:16:04.295
There was something wrong
with this person.

00:16:04.295 --> 00:16:06.820
Kind of made me feel -- then he
came later and asked me for

00:16:06.820 --> 00:16:07.970
a recommendation letter.

00:16:07.970 --> 00:16:12.450
I couldn't believe it after I
read about him in the Yale

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:13.700
Daily News.

00:16:15.830 --> 00:16:17.540
This is extreme.

00:16:17.540 --> 00:16:24.660
And so, incidentally, someone
did a study of APD by going to

00:16:24.660 --> 00:16:28.970
a prison and categorizing
the inmates

00:16:28.970 --> 00:16:30.850
using DSM-IV standards.

00:16:30.850 --> 00:16:35.700
And they found that 40% of
the prisoners had APD.

00:16:35.700 --> 00:16:38.380
Also, neuroscience people have
found that there are

00:16:38.380 --> 00:16:42.140
differences in the prefrontal
cortex that are

00:16:42.140 --> 00:16:43.580
correlated with APD.

00:16:43.580 --> 00:16:45.650
So it seems to be --

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:48.145
it's a problem we have in our
society that some people have

00:16:48.145 --> 00:16:50.690
a brain structure that's
a little different.

00:16:50.690 --> 00:16:54.310
And it may make it difficult
for them to

00:16:54.310 --> 00:16:55.775
behave in a good way.

00:17:01.089 --> 00:17:02.810
We're learning more and more
about neuroscience.

00:17:05.859 --> 00:17:08.530
It's interesting to me that Adam
Smith's book still rings

00:17:08.530 --> 00:17:09.829
true though after --

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:12.150
There's some basic common
sense that we all learn.

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:13.730
You have to judge people
and you have

00:17:13.730 --> 00:17:15.280
to learn their character.

00:17:15.280 --> 00:17:18.730
And you have to be a person of
character for, in the long

00:17:18.730 --> 00:17:21.230
run, that's what you want.

00:17:21.230 --> 00:17:23.180
It gives you what you
want in life.

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:39.860
Oh, another thing I wanted
to say is that people are

00:17:39.860 --> 00:17:40.860
manipulable.

00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:43.270
Unfortunately, true.

00:17:43.270 --> 00:17:49.850
And unfortunately, we live in
a world where it's hard to

00:17:49.850 --> 00:17:55.990
avoid manipulating people at
all, because we have a free

00:17:55.990 --> 00:17:59.810
enterprise system that
encourages competition.

00:17:59.810 --> 00:18:03.450
And if the competition is
manipulating people, how do

00:18:03.450 --> 00:18:07.110
you completely stay
clear of that?

00:18:07.110 --> 00:18:10.210
I think, this is one of the
contradictions of our society.

00:18:10.210 --> 00:18:14.720
A very simple and obvious
manipulation is, they'll put a

00:18:14.720 --> 00:18:20.950
price on some item they're
selling, like $9.99.

00:18:20.950 --> 00:18:23.670
So you're like, well, why didn't
they just say $10.00?

00:18:23.670 --> 00:18:24.825
Well, you know why
they didn't.

00:18:24.825 --> 00:18:27.730
It's called ''pricing points''
in marketing.

00:18:27.730 --> 00:18:31.720
Because $9.99 sounds
a lot less,

00:18:31.720 --> 00:18:33.980
psychologically, than $10.00.

00:18:33.980 --> 00:18:38.620
So, everyone does it, almost
everyone does it.

00:18:38.620 --> 00:18:42.130
But is that bad?

00:18:42.130 --> 00:18:43.210
Well, it's bad in a way.

00:18:43.210 --> 00:18:44.950
It's manipulative, isn't it?

00:18:44.950 --> 00:18:46.430
I mean I'm annoyed by it.

00:18:46.430 --> 00:18:47.910
Maybe you are, too.

00:18:47.910 --> 00:18:52.730
But if you were in business,
would you do that too?

00:18:52.730 --> 00:18:56.140
You might feel that you have to
and it's a harmless sort of

00:18:56.140 --> 00:18:57.990
manipulation.

00:18:57.990 --> 00:19:00.080
It's not hurting
anyone really.

00:19:00.080 --> 00:19:04.190
They're maybe buying a little
bit more than they want.

00:19:04.190 --> 00:19:08.420
See, that's the kind of
thing that comes in.

00:19:08.420 --> 00:19:12.970
So, in looking at financial
institutions, they're often

00:19:12.970 --> 00:19:14.490
manipulative in that sense.

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:19.540
It's similar to a politician.

00:19:19.540 --> 00:19:24.230
If you want to be a member of
Congress or whatever, you

00:19:24.230 --> 00:19:27.200
can't say what you
really believe.

00:19:27.200 --> 00:19:30.200
Because you won't get elected.

00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:34.360
You've got to kind of
doctor your opinions

00:19:34.360 --> 00:19:35.610
to the public opinion.

00:19:39.740 --> 00:19:42.080
But you might have a moral
purpose underlying it all,

00:19:42.080 --> 00:19:44.080
because you want to
get elected so

00:19:44.080 --> 00:19:45.330
you can do good things.

00:19:49.710 --> 00:19:51.320
So, you do end up
saying things.

00:19:51.320 --> 00:19:53.630
So, it's hard to judge
people, good or bad.

00:19:53.630 --> 00:19:57.410
It's an overall sense you get
of someone's character.

00:19:57.410 --> 00:19:59.520
That people are doing things
that appear somewhat

00:19:59.520 --> 00:20:03.930
manipulative and somewhat bad,
but you get an overall sense

00:20:03.930 --> 00:20:07.390
of the person through time.

00:20:07.390 --> 00:20:11.050
And ultimately, our society,
within limits, rewards people

00:20:11.050 --> 00:20:16.730
that show character through
all the confusing details.

00:20:16.730 --> 00:20:18.710
Now I wanted to move -- that
was my introduction.

00:20:18.710 --> 00:20:22.350
I wanted to move now to
discussing some particular

00:20:22.350 --> 00:20:25.800
aspects of Behavioral
Finance, or more

00:20:25.800 --> 00:20:28.300
broadly Behavioral Economics.

00:20:28.300 --> 00:20:37.445
And about human failings that
are exploitable by somebody

00:20:37.445 --> 00:20:45.520
and are somewhat exploited,
but remain.

00:20:45.520 --> 00:20:47.630
I wanted to start out with
what's probably the most

00:20:47.630 --> 00:20:51.460
famous element of Behavioral
Economics.

00:20:51.460 --> 00:21:01.820
It's Prospect Theory and
it was invented by two

00:21:01.820 --> 00:21:14.560
psychologists, Daniel Kahneman
and Amos Tversky, in the late

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:16.380
20th century.

00:21:16.380 --> 00:21:20.680
They called it Prospect Theory
because it was a theory of how

00:21:20.680 --> 00:21:24.150
people form decisions
about prospects.

00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:26.330
And a prospect is a gamble.

00:21:26.330 --> 00:21:28.270
It's about people's decisions
under uncertainty.

00:21:31.020 --> 00:21:37.390
And in very simple terms, the
Prospect Theory says --

00:21:37.390 --> 00:21:39.520
now there's a huge literature on
this, so I'm trying to give

00:21:39.520 --> 00:21:47.200
you a very quick description
of it.

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:50.920
That there's something called
a value function, which

00:21:50.920 --> 00:21:55.460
represents how people
value things.

00:21:58.450 --> 00:22:04.680
And there's a weighting
function, which shows how

00:22:04.680 --> 00:22:11.520
people infer or how they deal
with probabilities.

00:22:11.520 --> 00:22:15.610
And I just wrote simply what
Kahneman and Tversky say.

00:22:15.610 --> 00:22:18.680
I'll draw a picture of the
value function and the

00:22:18.680 --> 00:22:19.515
weighting function.

00:22:19.515 --> 00:22:24.650
And this will be very quick and
you'd have to read more,

00:22:24.650 --> 00:22:29.660
but the way people value
gains or losses --

00:22:29.660 --> 00:22:30.910
let me see.

00:22:33.334 --> 00:22:35.904
I better draw the line
in the middle.

00:22:39.280 --> 00:22:42.650
OK, and we're talking about
financial gains, so these are

00:22:42.650 --> 00:22:48.506
gains, and this is zero,
and this is losses.

00:22:48.506 --> 00:22:49.930
Well, negative.

00:22:49.930 --> 00:22:53.500
What I have on the horizontal
axis is wealth or money or

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:55.140
something like that.

00:22:55.140 --> 00:22:57.810
Zero in the middle.

00:22:57.810 --> 00:23:01.562
And then, we have on this
axis value, which is

00:23:01.562 --> 00:23:04.510
something like utility.

00:23:04.510 --> 00:23:10.660
I'll erase my zero, so it
doesn't get in the way.

00:23:10.660 --> 00:23:12.900
What they find is,
that people's

00:23:12.900 --> 00:23:15.740
value has a funny shape.

00:23:15.740 --> 00:23:19.150
We don't weigh gains and
losses linearly.

00:23:22.890 --> 00:23:26.122
In the positive quadrant, when
we have positive gains,

00:23:26.122 --> 00:23:30.800
there's diminishing
value like that.

00:23:30.800 --> 00:23:32.570
It doesn't ever slope down.

00:23:32.570 --> 00:23:37.900
It's concave down like
diminishing marginal utility

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:40.540
in economic theory.

00:23:40.540 --> 00:23:45.060
But for losses, it looks
something like this.

00:23:45.060 --> 00:23:47.550
It's concave up.

00:23:47.550 --> 00:23:50.710
I'm exaggerating a little bit,
but this is a diagram that

00:23:50.710 --> 00:23:58.150
Kahneman and Tversky wrote in
their famous Econometrica

00:23:58.150 --> 00:24:00.850
article 30 years ago.

00:24:00.850 --> 00:24:04.850
So, there's diminishing marginal
utility for gains,

00:24:04.850 --> 00:24:08.440
but there's the opposite --

00:24:08.440 --> 00:24:11.580
well, we have concave up.

00:24:11.580 --> 00:24:13.020
And there's a kink.

00:24:13.020 --> 00:24:16.620
Note that the value function
has a kink at the origin.

00:24:21.900 --> 00:24:25.030
So, what does this mean?

00:24:25.030 --> 00:24:30.010
OK, first of all, this
origin is a --

00:24:30.010 --> 00:24:34.500
from what point do I estimate
gains and losses?

00:24:34.500 --> 00:24:39.300
That's called the reference
point and it's psychological.

00:24:39.300 --> 00:24:41.570
And it's subject to
manipulation.

00:24:41.570 --> 00:24:43.740
The reference point
is the zero, from

00:24:43.740 --> 00:24:44.990
which I measure things.

00:24:48.280 --> 00:24:52.930
So, first of all, the reference
point is probably

00:24:52.930 --> 00:24:54.540
today's wealth.

00:24:54.540 --> 00:25:00.300
But it can be something else if
people are manipulated by

00:25:00.300 --> 00:25:03.860
the way something is
presented to them.

00:25:03.860 --> 00:25:09.300
Framing, according to Kahneman
and Tversky, is presentation.

00:25:09.300 --> 00:25:14.760
So, I can give the same prospect
to people, but word

00:25:14.760 --> 00:25:16.580
it in different ways
that suggests a

00:25:16.580 --> 00:25:18.840
different reference point.

00:25:18.840 --> 00:25:21.490
And that will change
people's behavior.

00:25:21.490 --> 00:25:25.620
So, you can manipulate people
by describing something in

00:25:25.620 --> 00:25:29.970
different terms, by suggesting
a different reference point.

00:25:29.970 --> 00:25:33.380
But typically, the reference
point is today's wealth.

00:25:33.380 --> 00:25:37.940
The kink means that people are
very conscious of little

00:25:37.940 --> 00:25:41.910
changes in their wealth and
they're spooked by them.

00:25:41.910 --> 00:25:45.540
I'm really afraid, because my
value drops very rapidly, even

00:25:45.540 --> 00:25:46.950
for a small loss.

00:25:46.950 --> 00:25:53.150
So, if you were to say,
lose $5 this morning.

00:25:53.150 --> 00:25:55.370
You had it in your pocket and
you lost it on the way to this

00:25:55.370 --> 00:25:59.810
lecture, you would feel
exaggeratedly bad about that.

00:25:59.810 --> 00:26:03.590
You should really regard $5 as
just nothing, because the

00:26:03.590 --> 00:26:05.740
present value of your lifetime
income is in the

00:26:05.740 --> 00:26:08.090
millions, so what's $5?

00:26:08.090 --> 00:26:10.090
But you don't think that way.

00:26:10.090 --> 00:26:16.120
So, you're spooked and deterred
by small losses, and

00:26:16.120 --> 00:26:19.940
less encouraged by
small gains.

00:26:19.940 --> 00:26:24.800
So, this kind of thing allows
businesspeople to exploit

00:26:24.800 --> 00:26:27.140
people if they want to.

00:26:27.140 --> 00:26:32.180
If people are so focused on
these little changes, then you

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:37.340
are encouraged in business to
try to pick things out the

00:26:37.340 --> 00:26:40.990
people are paying attention
to, like small things, and

00:26:40.990 --> 00:26:43.800
sell insurance policies
on just those things.

00:26:48.620 --> 00:26:51.590
Insurance should be concentrated
on the really big

00:26:51.590 --> 00:26:53.550
things, like life insurance.

00:26:53.550 --> 00:26:56.920
You know the fact that one of
your parents could die and the

00:26:56.920 --> 00:26:59.650
children's family would be
out of money for the

00:26:59.650 --> 00:27:00.610
rest of their lives.

00:27:00.610 --> 00:27:02.070
That's a big thing.

00:27:02.070 --> 00:27:06.050
But it may not work to sell
that kind of insurance.

00:27:06.050 --> 00:27:11.730
You can do something that is
more focused on what people

00:27:11.730 --> 00:27:15.230
are watching and make it
something little so that it

00:27:15.230 --> 00:27:17.830
doesn't require them to
spend so much money.

00:27:17.830 --> 00:27:21.115
The classic example of that
is funeral insurance.

00:27:26.260 --> 00:27:29.320
You go around telling people
-- and for some reason this

00:27:29.320 --> 00:27:32.260
sales pitch works, and it's
worked for thousands of years.

00:27:32.260 --> 00:27:34.850
They sold this in
Ancient Rome.

00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:38.630
You tell people, if someone in
your family dies, you can have

00:27:38.630 --> 00:27:41.855
an expense of getting a proper
burial for this person.

00:27:41.855 --> 00:27:43.560
It costs money.

00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:47.720
And so, they would insure
that one thing.

00:27:47.720 --> 00:27:52.930
And it was a little thing, but
it works to sell that.

00:27:52.930 --> 00:27:57.100
Another example of it is airline
flight insurance.

00:27:57.100 --> 00:28:01.410
You're insured for this flight
on the airplane.

00:28:01.410 --> 00:28:04.720
I heard an ad for funeral
insurance recently.

00:28:04.720 --> 00:28:08.120
They're still doing this after
2,000 years, because it still

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:10.110
works and it's manipulative.

00:28:10.110 --> 00:28:11.660
That's not what you should
do for people.

00:28:11.660 --> 00:28:14.040
You should not pick out
some little thing.

00:28:14.040 --> 00:28:16.150
Or they also have diamond
ring insurance.

00:28:16.150 --> 00:28:19.420
After an engagement, some women
will want to buy an

00:28:19.420 --> 00:28:21.560
insurance policy on the diamond,
because it can

00:28:21.560 --> 00:28:24.270
actually fall out of your
ring and you lose it.

00:28:24.270 --> 00:28:27.210
But that's like, what is it?
$5,000 or something?

00:28:27.210 --> 00:28:29.260
It's not big, it's
not essential.

00:28:29.260 --> 00:28:32.920
And if you're insuring that and
not other things, you're

00:28:32.920 --> 00:28:34.320
making a mistake.

00:28:34.320 --> 00:28:40.200
Fortunately, the insurance
industry is not too --

00:28:40.200 --> 00:28:42.800
it has come around to do
things that are more --

00:28:42.800 --> 00:28:45.020
they are doing things that
matter and are big.

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:48.975
And that's because this Kahneman
and Tversky value

00:28:48.975 --> 00:28:51.780
function is --

00:28:51.780 --> 00:28:55.060
it represents an error that
people are prone to be making.

00:28:55.060 --> 00:28:59.180
But it's not total
and not complete.

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:02.790
And so ultimately, people
don't go to insurance

00:29:02.790 --> 00:29:04.950
companies that manipulate
them.

00:29:04.950 --> 00:29:08.870
It gets around and eventually
people come around in wanting

00:29:08.870 --> 00:29:12.020
something better.

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:16.660
So, while there is some
manipulation, it's limited.

00:29:16.660 --> 00:29:18.820
The other aspect of Kahneman
and Tversky is

00:29:18.820 --> 00:29:20.070
the weighting function.

00:29:25.470 --> 00:29:30.090
I'm going to draw again
a picture of it.

00:29:30.090 --> 00:29:34.730
This time it's how people
psychologically think about

00:29:34.730 --> 00:29:36.300
probabilities.

00:29:36.300 --> 00:29:40.228
This again is Kahneman
and Tversky.

00:29:40.228 --> 00:29:46.065
A probability is a number
between 0 and 1 or 0 and 100%.

00:29:46.065 --> 00:29:50.490
I'll put 0 here and 1 here.

00:29:50.490 --> 00:29:53.390
We can tell someone the
probability of something, but

00:29:53.390 --> 00:29:56.440
they can't accept it
psychologically.

00:29:56.440 --> 00:29:59.710
The errors that people
make are described by

00:29:59.710 --> 00:30:01.580
the weighting function.

00:30:01.580 --> 00:30:04.690
What the waiting function is,
it's the psychological impact.

00:30:04.690 --> 00:30:08.090
You are behaving as if you
just don't understand the

00:30:08.090 --> 00:30:09.330
probability.

00:30:09.330 --> 00:30:14.020
So, what Kahneman and Tversky
say is, that for very low

00:30:14.020 --> 00:30:18.820
probabilities people may
round them to zero.

00:30:18.820 --> 00:30:21.090
And for very high probabilities,
they may round

00:30:21.090 --> 00:30:22.890
them to one.

00:30:22.890 --> 00:30:27.080
But if they decide not to round
them to zero or one,

00:30:27.080 --> 00:30:30.360
they exaggerate the difference
between zero and one.

00:30:30.360 --> 00:30:34.330
You just can't think in terms of
a continuum of probability.

00:30:34.330 --> 00:30:36.070
So, this is what the weighting
function --

00:30:36.070 --> 00:30:39.400
this is the weight as a function
of the probability.

00:30:39.400 --> 00:30:42.470
For low probabilities
it's zero.

00:30:42.470 --> 00:30:44.250
I'm going to maybe exaggerate
it here.

00:30:44.250 --> 00:30:47.100
Then it jumps up.

00:30:47.100 --> 00:30:50.260
It's something like this, and
as it gets close to one, it

00:30:50.260 --> 00:30:53.230
jumps up to one again.

00:30:53.230 --> 00:30:56.730
So you see, it's like a
broken line segment.

00:30:56.730 --> 00:30:59.050
And there's been various
versions of this theory, but

00:30:59.050 --> 00:31:02.160
this is the simplest
version of it.

00:31:02.160 --> 00:31:07.360
So that means, if you're getting
on an airplane, you

00:31:07.360 --> 00:31:08.660
think, well, what's
the probability of

00:31:08.660 --> 00:31:10.660
this airplane crashing?

00:31:10.660 --> 00:31:13.150
Well it's probably something
like 1 in 10

00:31:13.150 --> 00:31:14.260
million or, what is it?

00:31:14.260 --> 00:31:16.640
Even less than that.

00:31:16.640 --> 00:31:19.030
So most of us, in our
mind, just say, it's

00:31:19.030 --> 00:31:20.580
zero and I'm done.

00:31:20.580 --> 00:31:21.660
I'm not going to think about.

00:31:21.660 --> 00:31:23.460
I'm not going to
worry about it.

00:31:23.460 --> 00:31:24.300
So, we're down here.

00:31:24.300 --> 00:31:26.540
We've rounded it to zero.

00:31:26.540 --> 00:31:29.870
But some people don't
round it to zero.

00:31:29.870 --> 00:31:32.730
And for them, they just blow
it out of all proportion in

00:31:32.730 --> 00:31:35.050
their minds, and it becomes
exaggerated.

00:31:35.050 --> 00:31:37.980
So, I have it here, so it
looks like it's a half.

00:31:37.980 --> 00:31:45.030
This would be one here and
this is about 0.4.

00:31:45.030 --> 00:31:47.680
And then ultimately, if the
probability gets really high,

00:31:47.680 --> 00:31:49.940
then I'm not even going to
think about it, it's one.

00:31:53.950 --> 00:31:57.090
In some of the most primitive
languages in the world,

00:31:57.090 --> 00:31:59.930
there's only a couple
of numbers.

00:31:59.930 --> 00:32:00.900
There's zero.

00:32:00.900 --> 00:32:02.190
There's one.

00:32:02.190 --> 00:32:03.835
Maybe there's two or
three, and then

00:32:03.835 --> 00:32:05.040
there's no more numbers.

00:32:05.040 --> 00:32:08.870
Well, our minds are still very
primitive in dealing with

00:32:08.870 --> 00:32:09.850
probability.

00:32:09.850 --> 00:32:12.530
So it's like there's only
three probabilities.

00:32:12.530 --> 00:32:17.610
Can't happen, may be,
and will happen.

00:32:17.610 --> 00:32:20.400
So, I think airline flight
insurance is an example of

00:32:20.400 --> 00:32:25.600
trying to manipulate this
personality characteristic.

00:32:25.600 --> 00:32:31.500
So, it means that they'll
catch all the people who

00:32:31.500 --> 00:32:33.340
exaggerate it.

00:32:33.340 --> 00:32:36.970
They used to have vending
machines outside of airlines.

00:32:36.970 --> 00:32:42.510
The vending machines would
encourage you to buy just for

00:32:42.510 --> 00:32:44.170
this flight.

00:32:44.170 --> 00:32:46.580
They put it right there when
you're getting on the flight.

00:32:46.580 --> 00:32:48.210
And so that's when you're
most nervous.

00:32:48.210 --> 00:32:50.800
If you're one of these
people who's up here.

00:32:50.800 --> 00:32:52.520
