the correct answer.

00:47:46.250 --> 00:47:50.490
So, the world population
as of 8:00 a.m.

00:47:50.490 --> 00:47:52.670
this morning
[addition: February 21, 2011]

00:47:52.670 --> 00:48:06.400
was 6,901,330,581.

00:48:06.400 --> 00:48:10.480
Now, can I get a show of hands,
how many peoples'

00:48:10.480 --> 00:48:13.260
confidence interval includes
that number?

00:48:16.320 --> 00:48:18.570
OK, can someone tell me
what percent that is?

00:48:18.570 --> 00:48:20.130
That is not 90%.

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:22.240
You're doing pretty
well, though.

00:48:22.240 --> 00:48:23.980
What do you think, Oliver?

00:48:23.980 --> 00:48:24.850
STUDENT: About 80.

00:48:24.850 --> 00:48:26.290
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER:
You think it's 80?

00:48:26.290 --> 00:48:29.820
Let me see them up again.

00:48:29.820 --> 00:48:30.870
Maybe it is 80, all right.

00:48:30.870 --> 00:48:34.050
You're doing really well.

00:48:34.050 --> 00:48:37.190
Some honest people here didn't
put their hands up.

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:38.120
All right, well, that's one.

00:48:38.120 --> 00:48:40.430
So, we did 80 instead of 90.

00:48:40.430 --> 00:48:43.440
What about the weight
of the earth?

00:48:43.440 --> 00:48:55.970
In kilograms. Well, it's 5.974
times 10 to 24th power.

00:48:55.970 --> 00:49:00.220
And I'll give you
that in tons.

00:49:00.220 --> 00:49:08.000
It's 5,974 billion
billion tons.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:09.330
You got that?

00:49:09.330 --> 00:49:11.500
You might have to do
some calculation.

00:49:11.500 --> 00:49:15.907
It'd be 5.9734 times 10
to the 18th power.

00:49:15.907 --> 00:49:16.150
[correction: 5,974 times
10 to the 18th power is

00:49:16.150 --> 00:49:17.260
the weight in tons.]

00:49:17.260 --> 00:49:18.360
OK, can we do a show of hands?

00:49:18.360 --> 00:49:21.260
How many people had
a number in --

00:49:21.260 --> 00:49:24.480
how many people are in the
confidence interval there.

00:49:24.480 --> 00:49:26.510
All right, Oliver, what
do you think?

00:49:26.510 --> 00:49:27.792
What's the fraction?

00:49:27.792 --> 00:49:29.240
STUDENT: 5%, maybe 10.

00:49:29.240 --> 00:49:29.670
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: 10%.

00:49:29.670 --> 00:49:30.430
OK.

00:49:30.430 --> 00:49:34.180
So this one, we did really
well on world population.

00:49:34.180 --> 00:49:35.770
80, 10.

00:49:35.770 --> 00:49:39.370
The last one, how many languages
are in the world?

00:49:39.370 --> 00:49:44.450
Well, according to
ethnologue.com there are 6,909

00:49:44.450 --> 00:49:47.920
languages this morning
[addition: February 21, 2011].

00:49:47.920 --> 00:49:49.780
How many people got that within

00:49:49.780 --> 00:49:52.040
their confidence interval?

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:54.620
OK, what do you think, Oliver?

00:49:54.620 --> 00:49:55.480
STUDENT: About the same, 10%.

00:49:55.480 --> 00:49:57.380
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER:
10%, OK.

00:49:57.380 --> 00:49:59.450
Why did you do so much better
on world population?

00:50:02.250 --> 00:50:04.370
Well, thank you for being
honest with me.

00:50:04.370 --> 00:50:08.340
I think it worked once again.

00:50:08.340 --> 00:50:09.590
The overconfidence.

00:50:09.590 --> 00:50:13.080
So, why is it that people are
overconfident like this?

00:50:13.080 --> 00:50:21.770
And psychologists have tried to
describe, what it is that

00:50:21.770 --> 00:50:25.170
goes on in people's minds that
produces answers like this.

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:28.620
One of them is, that people seem
to have a sense that they

00:50:28.620 --> 00:50:31.580
understand the world more
than they really do.

00:50:31.580 --> 00:50:33.140
It's an illusion.

00:50:33.140 --> 00:50:36.510
Actually, the world is just
infinitely complicated and

00:50:36.510 --> 00:50:37.760
there are so many surprises.

00:50:40.520 --> 00:50:42.260
When you think about a question
like this, there's

00:50:42.260 --> 00:50:45.750
many different perspectives
that you can take.

00:50:45.750 --> 00:50:49.790
And if you thought more about
it, your imagination might

00:50:49.790 --> 00:50:52.020
help you to widen your
confidence interval.

00:50:52.020 --> 00:50:55.110
But you can't think of all
the perspectives at once.

00:50:55.110 --> 00:50:59.600
And so, you tend to gravitate to
the first one that comes to

00:50:59.600 --> 00:51:04.670
mind and it gives you an
underestimate of the

00:51:04.670 --> 00:51:05.920
confidence.

00:51:10.080 --> 00:51:13.130
So, that is overconfidence.

00:51:13.130 --> 00:51:15.770
By the way, I think it's a
little bit higher in males

00:51:15.770 --> 00:51:17.250
than females.

00:51:17.250 --> 00:51:19.520
I didn't do a separate
male/female count.

00:51:19.520 --> 00:51:20.440
But females [correction: males]

00:51:20.440 --> 00:51:23.180
are definitely overconfident.

00:51:23.180 --> 00:51:26.140
That's the so-called macho
personality that's supremely

00:51:26.140 --> 00:51:30.140
overconfident, which is --
that's not in DSM-IV. I don't

00:51:30.140 --> 00:51:33.650
think it is, but it is more
common among males.

00:51:33.650 --> 00:51:37.110
But it's really, everyone
is overconfident.

00:51:37.110 --> 00:51:41.780
There's no important sex
difference here.

00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:44.540
Incidentally, I think that
overconfidence, and this is an

00:51:44.540 --> 00:51:47.612
important phenomenon, it
goes beyond yourself.

00:51:47.612 --> 00:51:49.455
It extends to your friends.

00:51:52.170 --> 00:51:55.330
And you exaggerate --

00:51:55.330 --> 00:51:57.500
there's a tendency for people
to think that I have very

00:51:57.500 --> 00:51:58.750
smart friends.

00:52:01.030 --> 00:52:02.290
I was reflecting
the other day.

00:52:02.290 --> 00:52:05.910
When I was an undergraduate at
University of Michigan, I was

00:52:05.910 --> 00:52:08.720
in the honors program and we
thought we were pretty smart.

00:52:08.720 --> 00:52:13.130
And I had a number of young
people that I just imagined

00:52:13.130 --> 00:52:17.840
were heading toward really
great careers.

00:52:17.840 --> 00:52:22.190
There was one student that we
called Young Jack Kennedy.

00:52:22.190 --> 00:52:23.770
You know, this was
some years ago.

00:52:23.770 --> 00:52:25.560
Jack Kennedy was president
of the United States.

00:52:25.560 --> 00:52:26.730
We thought he was a genius.

00:52:26.730 --> 00:52:28.940
That was probably wrong, too.

00:52:28.940 --> 00:52:32.050
None of these people
are geniuses.

00:52:32.050 --> 00:52:37.020
I was thinking that most of my
friends ended up in very good

00:52:37.020 --> 00:52:42.150
careers, but nothing that you
would think was spectacular.

00:52:42.150 --> 00:52:45.530
I had one friend as an
undergrad, who I thought was a

00:52:45.530 --> 00:52:50.400
genius, and his name was
Bruce Wasserstein.

00:52:50.400 --> 00:52:52.180
Anyone ever heard of him?

00:52:52.180 --> 00:52:53.700
Maybe not.

00:52:53.700 --> 00:52:54.790
Well see, that's it.

00:52:54.790 --> 00:52:57.430
But he founded his own
investment bank called

00:52:57.430 --> 00:53:02.620
Wasserstein Perella, became
really rich and then he bought

00:53:02.620 --> 00:53:08.100
interest in Lazard Freres, the
French investment bank.

00:53:08.100 --> 00:53:09.970
He was a real big shot
on Wall Street.

00:53:09.970 --> 00:53:14.860
I met him again about 10 years
ago and then he died.

00:53:14.860 --> 00:53:16.000
God.

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:18.720
He had a heart attack
and died.

00:53:18.720 --> 00:53:19.860
So, I know his whole life.

00:53:19.860 --> 00:53:22.950
I saw him when he was 18 and
I've watched his whole life,

00:53:22.950 --> 00:53:23.910
and it's now history.

00:53:23.910 --> 00:53:25.900
It's kind of scary.

00:53:25.900 --> 00:53:29.480
But I remember thinking he was
a genius as an undergrad.

00:53:29.480 --> 00:53:31.410
I was wondering, what was
wrong with my judgment?

00:53:31.410 --> 00:53:33.055
Why did I see so many
other geniuses?

00:53:37.590 --> 00:53:41.620
Now that I think back on it,
he had a sort of real world

00:53:41.620 --> 00:53:44.140
common sense that amazed me.

00:53:47.040 --> 00:53:50.170
He just knew things that --
it wasn't fake knowledge.

00:53:50.170 --> 00:53:53.050
He seemed to know how
things worked.

00:53:53.050 --> 00:53:54.760
So, I guess I was right
about one of them.

00:53:54.760 --> 00:53:58.560
But not enough that none of you
have heard of him right?

00:53:58.560 --> 00:54:00.830
He has an investment bank
named after him.

00:54:00.830 --> 00:54:04.530
You should have heard of
him, but maybe not.

00:54:04.530 --> 00:54:07.110
But anyway, this thing affects
peoples' thinking, too.

00:54:07.110 --> 00:54:09.960
I think that we tend to think
that the head of state who is

00:54:09.960 --> 00:54:14.180
running, the head of our central
bank is a genius.

00:54:14.180 --> 00:54:17.920
And this really clouds
our thinking.

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:21.380
It's like our ego extends to
the other people that we

00:54:21.380 --> 00:54:23.190
associate with ourselves.

00:54:23.190 --> 00:54:25.460
Now, the head of a central bank
in another country we

00:54:25.460 --> 00:54:26.910
have no respect for.

00:54:26.910 --> 00:54:29.590
It's only in our own country,
because it's part of our ego

00:54:29.590 --> 00:54:31.820
involvement that produces
this overconfidence.

00:54:37.710 --> 00:54:40.100
This tendency for overconfidence
produces a lot

00:54:40.100 --> 00:54:44.290
of anomalies and opportunities
for manipulation.

00:54:44.290 --> 00:54:49.715
So, for example, Rakesh Khurana,
who is a professor at

00:54:49.715 --> 00:54:57.310
the Harvard Business School,
has written a book called

00:54:57.310 --> 00:55:01.370
Search for the Charismatic
CEO.

00:55:01.370 --> 00:55:05.970
He claims that there's a
tendency for people to think

00:55:05.970 --> 00:55:08.410
that CEOs are geniuses.

00:55:08.410 --> 00:55:11.940
Or at least the one that
we found is a genius.

00:55:11.940 --> 00:55:16.970
And companies then seek out a
genius CEO to put in charge of

00:55:16.970 --> 00:55:19.770
the company as a kind
of manipulation

00:55:19.770 --> 00:55:21.250
of the stock market.

00:55:21.250 --> 00:55:28.670
They think if we get -- you
know, if we got some guy who's

00:55:28.670 --> 00:55:31.510
run other companies successfully
in the past, he

00:55:31.510 --> 00:55:32.370
must be a genius.

00:55:32.370 --> 00:55:35.410
Put him in our company, our
stock price will go up, then

00:55:35.410 --> 00:55:37.810
we can sell our executive --

00:55:37.810 --> 00:55:41.330
we can exercise our options
and make a lot of money by

00:55:41.330 --> 00:55:43.270
putting in this fake genius.

00:55:43.270 --> 00:55:48.880
And Khurana says, well, there
are some people who are maybe

00:55:48.880 --> 00:55:50.930
geniuses at management,
but most of the time

00:55:50.930 --> 00:55:52.300
they're just lucky.

00:55:52.300 --> 00:55:55.350
And we tend to develop
overconfidence.

00:55:55.350 --> 00:55:58.190
And then what happens, according
to Khurana, is, you

00:55:58.190 --> 00:56:00.760
put in some guy who turned
around some company

00:56:00.760 --> 00:56:03.370
spectacularly, supposedly.

00:56:03.370 --> 00:56:06.390
You bring him in to run a new
company and he doesn't know

00:56:06.390 --> 00:56:09.030
anything about this
new company.

00:56:09.030 --> 00:56:12.730
But he has to justify himself,
so he lays off a lot of people

00:56:12.730 --> 00:56:16.020
and shuffles things around, and
just destroys everything

00:56:16.020 --> 00:56:20.240
in the company, and
ruins things.

00:56:20.240 --> 00:56:25.480
This is related to another
author that I recommend.

00:56:25.480 --> 00:56:26.940
I've mentioned him
before, I think.

00:56:29.570 --> 00:56:33.315
Nassim Taleb wrote a book called
Fooled by Randomness.

00:56:37.990 --> 00:56:46.070
He's Lebanese, but now in the
U.S. Nassim Taleb, Fooled by

00:56:46.070 --> 00:56:52.660
Randomness, that says that most
of the things that happen

00:56:52.660 --> 00:56:55.430
in life are just chance.

00:56:55.430 --> 00:56:57.370
We tend to ascribe them.

00:56:57.370 --> 00:57:00.140
If they happen to us,
we conclude --

00:57:00.140 --> 00:57:01.800
we're very quick to conclude
that it's a

00:57:01.800 --> 00:57:04.170
sign of our own genius.

00:57:04.170 --> 00:57:07.230
And if it happens to someone
that is a friend of us, then

00:57:07.230 --> 00:57:11.570
you think, well, I have genius
friends, isn't that nice?

00:57:11.570 --> 00:57:13.405
And so, it leads to mistakes.

00:57:18.230 --> 00:57:21.000
OK, let me go to another --

00:57:21.000 --> 00:57:22.050
how much time do I have --

00:57:22.050 --> 00:57:25.510
cognitive dissonance.

00:57:25.510 --> 00:57:27.430
This is another psychological
principle.

00:57:31.152 --> 00:57:40.510
The term was coined by
sociologist Leon Festinger in

00:57:40.510 --> 00:57:42.590
the 1950s, I believe.

00:57:42.590 --> 00:57:44.660
I actually met this guy.

00:57:44.660 --> 00:57:46.620
That's the nice thing about
being in academia, you meet

00:57:46.620 --> 00:57:49.130
all these great names if
you're in long enough,

00:57:49.130 --> 00:57:51.290
eventually.

00:57:51.290 --> 00:57:54.290
But what is cognitive
dissonance?

00:57:54.290 --> 00:57:59.540
It's a judgmental bias that
people tend to make, because

00:57:59.540 --> 00:58:01.600
they don't want to admit
they're wrong.

00:58:01.600 --> 00:58:03.550
Maybe I'm oversimplifying
this mistake.

00:58:03.550 --> 00:58:07.470
It's painful to think, that I
believe something and it was

00:58:07.470 --> 00:58:13.710
wrong, so people will cling to
old beliefs and try to find

00:58:13.710 --> 00:58:16.050
evidence that supports their
beliefs, because they have an

00:58:16.050 --> 00:58:19.380
ego involvement with
the belief.

00:58:19.380 --> 00:58:20.760
And so, I will be biased.

00:58:20.760 --> 00:58:23.800
The famous experiment
indicating cognitive

00:58:23.800 --> 00:58:26.170
dissonance, done by some
psychologist, had the

00:58:26.170 --> 00:58:27.720
following form.

00:58:27.720 --> 00:58:30.960
They got a list of people who
had just bought a car and they

00:58:30.960 --> 00:58:32.420
knew what make of car.

00:58:32.420 --> 00:58:35.360
They got the list from car
dealers, so they knew exactly

00:58:35.360 --> 00:58:37.630
what car they had just bought.

00:58:37.630 --> 00:58:39.450
And they called these people
up and asked them to

00:58:39.450 --> 00:58:41.350
participate in a psych
experiment.

00:58:41.350 --> 00:58:43.750
Or I think they said a
marketing experiment.

00:58:43.750 --> 00:58:46.240
They didn't let them know that
they knew what car they had

00:58:46.240 --> 00:58:47.360
just bought.

00:58:47.360 --> 00:58:49.700
And then, the experiment
was the following.

00:58:49.700 --> 00:58:53.050
Let's go through a number of --
what magazines do you read?

00:58:53.050 --> 00:58:54.430
And they said, let's
get these out.

00:58:54.430 --> 00:58:57.030
They got all the magazines that
were on the newsstand.

00:58:57.030 --> 00:58:59.560
And they said, let's look
through page by page and tell

00:58:59.560 --> 00:59:02.770
us which ads you remember
reading.

00:59:02.770 --> 00:59:06.250
What they found is, that people
read the ads for the

00:59:06.250 --> 00:59:08.990
car they just bought.

00:59:08.990 --> 00:59:14.190
And they avoided especially the
car that they thought they

00:59:14.190 --> 00:59:16.900
might buy, but decided
not to buy.

00:59:16.900 --> 00:59:20.220
So, after you buy a car,
you want to confirm

00:59:20.220 --> 00:59:21.130
your belief in it.

00:59:21.130 --> 00:59:24.040
So, you selectively get
information that

00:59:24.040 --> 00:59:26.450
confirms your belief.

00:59:26.450 --> 00:59:31.470
And so, this cognitive
dissonance is another factor.

00:59:31.470 --> 00:59:32.530
It's been demonstrated.

00:59:32.530 --> 00:59:33.920
It's an error that
people make.

00:59:33.920 --> 00:59:35.380
It doesn't mean that people --

00:59:35.380 --> 00:59:38.290
again, none of these
errors is unviable.

00:59:38.290 --> 00:59:41.030
People will make the error and
then they'll learn from their

00:59:41.030 --> 00:59:42.590
mistakes and they'll correct.

00:59:42.590 --> 00:59:46.060
They're not totally cognitive
dissonant, but it's just a

00:59:46.060 --> 00:59:49.250
kind of error that
keeps coming up.

00:59:49.250 --> 00:59:52.700
So, I give you a couple of
examples of cognitive

00:59:52.700 --> 00:59:55.500
dissonance and its effects
on finance.

00:59:55.500 --> 01:00:00.620
So, Will Goetzmann, who is a
professor here at the Yale

01:00:00.620 --> 01:00:05.390
School of Management, and a
couple of his co-authors found

01:00:05.390 --> 01:00:09.040
that mutual fund investors --

01:00:09.040 --> 01:00:12.140
when a mutual fund does very
badly in its investment

01:00:12.140 --> 01:00:16.960
performance, many or most
investors sell the stock and

01:00:16.960 --> 01:00:17.660
get out of it.

01:00:17.660 --> 01:00:21.060
But some of them hang on.

01:00:21.060 --> 01:00:23.750
And they thought that that was
due, perhaps, to cognitive

01:00:23.750 --> 01:00:24.290
dissonance.

01:00:24.290 --> 01:00:31.470
Because I bought this fund,
I don't want to sell

01:00:31.470 --> 01:00:35.430
because I was right.

01:00:35.430 --> 01:00:38.190
So, what they did is, they
interviewed these people and

01:00:38.190 --> 01:00:42.080
they found that these people
didn't even know how badly the

01:00:42.080 --> 01:00:42.795
fund has done.

01:00:42.795 --> 01:00:46.240
They had blocked it out and
they had an exaggerated

01:00:46.240 --> 01:00:47.490
impression.

01:00:52.135 --> 01:00:55.080
An exaggerated impression of
this, which is characteristic

01:00:55.080 --> 01:00:56.380
of cognitive dissonance.

01:00:56.380 --> 01:01:00.930
You just forget the evidence
that's contrary to your theory

01:01:00.930 --> 01:01:02.890
and you keep assembling
evidence that

01:01:02.890 --> 01:01:05.150
supports your theory.

01:01:05.150 --> 01:01:09.970
I have another example of
cognitive dissonance and this

01:01:09.970 --> 01:01:17.290
one was produced by Professor
Sendhil Mullainathan at the

01:01:17.290 --> 01:01:20.940
Harvard Economics Department.

01:01:20.940 --> 01:01:26.120
And Mullainathan looked at
financial advisors --

01:01:26.120 --> 01:01:27.370
and his co-authors.

01:01:29.410 --> 01:01:32.010
What they did in this study --

01:01:32.010 --> 01:01:33.590
that's a whole big profession.

01:01:33.590 --> 01:01:35.750
I remember at the beginning I
pointed out how many hundreds

01:01:35.750 --> 01:01:38.380
of thousands of financial
advisors there are.

01:01:38.380 --> 01:01:40.640
What they did, it's an
interesting experiment.

01:01:40.640 --> 01:01:45.290
They hired actors to go to
financial advisors and ask for

01:01:45.290 --> 01:01:46.780
their help.

01:01:46.780 --> 01:01:50.370
And the experiment was
the following.

01:01:50.370 --> 01:01:55.650
They would say the same thing to
each financial advisor, but

01:01:55.650 --> 01:01:58.600
the different actors would
present their existing

01:01:58.600 --> 01:02:00.370
portfolio differently.

01:02:00.370 --> 01:02:03.640
In other words, you'd go to the
advisor and you'd say, I

01:02:03.640 --> 01:02:08.470
have a portfolio of investments
and I'm almost

01:02:08.470 --> 01:02:11.050
entirely in money
market funds.

01:02:11.050 --> 01:02:11.450
That's all.

01:02:11.450 --> 01:02:12.130
You'd just say that.

01:02:12.130 --> 01:02:14.620
You wouldn't express
any opinion at all.

01:02:14.620 --> 01:02:17.960
Another actor would go and
say, I've got all of my

01:02:17.960 --> 01:02:21.460
portfolio in tech stocks.

01:02:21.460 --> 01:02:24.720
Or I've got all of my portfolio
in options.

01:02:24.720 --> 01:02:27.190
Now, what should advisors
tell people?

01:02:27.190 --> 01:02:30.700
Well, if they were acting really
professionally, they

01:02:30.700 --> 01:02:33.910
should question the assumptions
that made the

01:02:33.910 --> 01:02:36.950
actor supposedly put all their
money in one kind of

01:02:36.950 --> 01:02:39.300
investment.

01:02:39.300 --> 01:02:42.300
And many of the financial
advisors did, but

01:02:42.300 --> 01:02:44.920
usually they didn't.

01:02:44.920 --> 01:02:49.650
They didn't question
the actor.

01:02:49.650 --> 01:02:54.660
They assumed that the actor, who
had put, supposedly, all

01:02:54.660 --> 01:02:58.800
of the investments in money
market funds, was someone who

01:02:58.800 --> 01:03:04.640
was very risk averse, or thought
that was the right

01:03:04.640 --> 01:03:05.410
thing to do.

01:03:05.410 --> 01:03:08.220
And they didn't want to
challenge them, so they would

01:03:08.220 --> 01:03:10.740
walk out of there with maybe
a slightly different mix of

01:03:10.740 --> 01:03:12.170
money market funds.

01:03:12.170 --> 01:03:15.140
And somebody else who was in a
very risky portfolio, they

01:03:15.140 --> 01:03:17.340
didn't challenge them.

01:03:17.340 --> 01:03:22.140
And they even sent actors in
with almost all of their

01:03:22.140 --> 01:03:25.680
portfolio in their own
company's stock.

01:03:25.680 --> 01:03:28.350
Now if you work for Ford
Motor Company --

01:03:28.350 --> 01:03:30.100
I noticed my uncle --

01:03:30.100 --> 01:03:32.200
I had conversations with
him about this --

01:03:32.200 --> 01:03:35.420
who worked for Ford Motor
Company and put all of his

01:03:35.420 --> 01:03:38.250
life savings in Ford
Motor Company.

01:03:38.250 --> 01:03:41.740
I said, Uncle Ralph, you
shouldn't do that.

01:03:41.740 --> 01:03:44.930
Because it's your job and all
of your life savings.

01:03:44.930 --> 01:03:47.180
What if something happened
to Ford Motor Company?

01:03:47.180 --> 01:03:49.730
Fortunately, he didn't
work for GM, which

01:03:49.730 --> 01:03:51.680
became worthless recently.

01:03:51.680 --> 01:03:52.660
But it can happen.

01:03:52.660 --> 01:03:55.150
You know, Ford could be
completely wiped out.

01:03:55.150 --> 01:03:56.890
That's your life savings.

01:03:56.890 --> 01:03:59.500
And you know what
he said to me?

01:03:59.500 --> 01:04:02.690
He said, you know, I've worked
at Ford all my life.

01:04:02.690 --> 01:04:04.830
They treat me well, I
believe in them, I'm

01:04:04.830 --> 01:04:07.600
not going to sell.

01:04:07.600 --> 01:04:09.130
So, there's lots of
people like that.

01:04:09.130 --> 01:04:11.780
So, when they show up at a
financial advisor, the first

01:04:11.780 --> 01:04:15.100
thing that they should do, the
financial advisor should tell

01:04:15.100 --> 01:04:18.580
them, get out of your
Ford stock.

01:04:18.580 --> 01:04:20.250
That's just too risky.

01:04:20.250 --> 01:04:24.695
But only 40% of the financial
advisors did that.

01:04:24.695 --> 01:04:29.720
The 60% left them mostly in
their own company stock.

01:04:29.720 --> 01:04:31.000
Why did they do that?

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:33.890
Well, Mullainathan thought, it's
because the advisors know

01:04:33.890 --> 01:04:37.220
there's cognitive dissonance,
and they're afraid to drive

01:04:37.220 --> 01:04:39.070
away a new client.

01:04:39.070 --> 01:04:42.120
Maybe they'll gradually do it
over a while, but you just

01:04:42.120 --> 01:04:44.640
don't challenge their
deep beliefs,

01:04:44.640 --> 01:04:46.580
whatever they say is true.

01:04:46.580 --> 01:04:48.430
And so, they're kind
of yes-men.

01:04:48.430 --> 01:04:52.000
Not all of them, and maybe
they'll come around.

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:54.950
It relates then, again,
to a moral dilemma.

01:04:54.950 --> 01:04:59.520
If you are a financial advisor
working in private practice,

01:04:59.520 --> 01:05:03.940
what do you do with people who
come to you, if you know from

01:05:03.940 --> 01:05:07.330
experience that challenging
their deep-seated beliefs will

01:05:07.330 --> 01:05:08.990
drive them away?

01:05:08.990 --> 01:05:11.320
So, in the real world,
this is again --

01:05:11.320 --> 01:05:13.630
I'm not sure that these
financial advisors are doing

01:05:13.630 --> 01:05:15.630
the wrong thing.

01:05:15.630 --> 01:05:19.430
If they would eventually tilt
them toward a more responsible

01:05:19.430 --> 01:05:21.920
portfolio, they can't
drive them away.

01:05:32.640 --> 01:05:34.330
I have a lot of -- so many.

01:05:34.330 --> 01:05:37.900
Let me list some of the
others and move on.

01:05:37.900 --> 01:05:39.710
What else should I talk about?

01:05:39.710 --> 01:05:40.960
Anchoring.

01:05:50.850 --> 01:05:59.000
Anchoring refers to a tendency
to anchor your opinions on

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:02.330
something that captures
your attention.

01:06:02.330 --> 01:06:05.730
The famous anchoring experiment
by, it was again,

01:06:05.730 --> 01:06:06.980
Kahneman and Tversky --

01:06:09.730 --> 01:06:12.015
I could almost do this
experiment here in class with

01:06:12.015 --> 01:06:13.045
you if I had a wheel
of fortune.

01:06:13.045 --> 01:06:15.800
A wheel of fortune is
like on a game show.

01:06:15.800 --> 01:06:19.360
You spin the wheel and it comes
up with a number between

01:06:19.360 --> 01:06:23.540
zero and a hundred in this
particular wheel of fortune.

01:06:23.540 --> 01:06:25.140
So, this is the experiment.

01:06:25.140 --> 01:06:28.720
They asked their subjects,
how many people --

01:06:28.720 --> 01:06:30.580
it had to be something
that had an answer

01:06:30.580 --> 01:06:31.650
from zero to a hundred.

01:06:31.650 --> 01:06:36.470
One of their questions was, how
many nations in the world

01:06:36.470 --> 01:06:36.650
[addition: in percent]

01:06:36.650 --> 01:06:39.680
belong to the United Nations?

01:06:39.680 --> 01:06:40.605
So, they asked the question.

01:06:40.605 --> 01:06:42.420
They said, don't answer
me just yet.

01:06:42.420 --> 01:06:44.010
Think about that question.

01:06:44.010 --> 01:06:47.080
What percent of nations
in the world belong

01:06:47.080 --> 01:06:48.080
to the United Nations.

01:06:48.080 --> 01:06:50.750
Then, they spun the wheel, and
it came up and it showed a

01:06:50.750 --> 01:06:52.840
random number.

01:06:52.840 --> 01:06:54.830
And then, they asked people
for the answer.

01:06:54.830 --> 01:06:57.320
Well, it turns out that people
tended to give an answer close

01:06:57.320 --> 01:07:00.170
to the number that just
came up on the wheel.

01:07:00.170 --> 01:07:03.560
This is totally irrational,
right?

01:07:03.560 --> 01:07:05.360
That wheel has nothing to
do with the answer.

01:07:05.360 --> 01:07:07.620
And yet people were
influenced by it.

01:07:07.620 --> 01:07:10.500
So then, they would follow-up
and ask them, hey, that number

01:07:10.500 --> 01:07:12.401
you gave is the same as the one
that just came up on the

01:07:12.401 --> 01:07:14.270
wheel, or it's close to it.

01:07:14.270 --> 01:07:15.470
Why did you do that?

01:07:15.470 --> 01:07:17.360
The guy would say,
just coincidence.

01:07:17.360 --> 01:07:18.630
I wasn't influenced
by the wheel.

01:07:18.630 --> 01:07:19.960
Of course not.

01:07:19.960 --> 01:07:22.540
But you know they were, because
statistically they

01:07:22.540 --> 01:07:24.110
proved that they were.

01:07:24.110 --> 01:07:29.960
So, anchoring means that people
are attracted to --

01:07:29.960 --> 01:07:36.630
they're affected by subconscious
things.

01:07:36.630 --> 01:07:38.300
I shouldn't say subconscious.

01:07:38.300 --> 01:07:40.590
They didn't make a logical
connection.

01:07:40.590 --> 01:07:43.375
When you face real ambiguity and
you don't know the answer

01:07:43.375 --> 01:07:46.340
and you've got to come up with
a decision, you are swayed by

01:07:46.340 --> 01:07:49.320
the most silly and
random things.

01:07:49.320 --> 01:07:50.950
There's a representativeness
heuristic.

01:07:58.580 --> 01:07:59.930
This is also Kahneman
and Tversky.

01:08:02.440 --> 01:08:05.960
And that is, that people
overemphasize certain patterns

01:08:05.960 --> 01:08:08.720
that they think are
representative of what they've

01:08:08.720 --> 01:08:10.380
seen before.

01:08:10.380 --> 01:08:14.250
So for example, certain patterns
in the stock market

01:08:14.250 --> 01:08:18.279
that may be very rare
and unusual.

01:08:18.279 --> 01:08:20.750
If they remember it, if it
somehow attracted their

01:08:20.750 --> 01:08:23.080
attention, they begin
to look for that

01:08:23.080 --> 01:08:25.710
pattern again and again.

01:08:25.710 --> 01:08:29.090
And they see it too often.

01:08:29.090 --> 01:08:31.290
So for example, Head
and Shoulders, we

01:08:31.290 --> 01:08:32.649
talked about that.

01:08:32.649 --> 01:08:37.340
McGee, the technical analyst, he
saw the Head and Shoulders

01:08:37.340 --> 01:08:38.779
pattern in the stock market.

01:08:38.779 --> 01:08:40.939
And he saw that it crashed
after that.

01:08:40.939 --> 01:08:42.890
But actually, it's pretty
hard to find those,

01:08:42.890 --> 01:08:44.050
they're kind of rare.

01:08:44.050 --> 01:08:47.250
And it's not the right way to
process data, to be looking

01:08:47.250 --> 01:08:49.020
for patterns that are
representative.

01:08:49.020 --> 01:08:51.140
And it invites manipulation.

01:08:51.140 --> 01:08:53.229
So, I'll give you some
other bad behavior.

01:08:53.229 --> 01:08:56.240
If people believe in the Head
and Shoulders, if they believe

01:08:56.240 --> 01:08:59.149
that the Head and Shoulders
pattern of stock price

01:08:59.149 --> 01:09:03.080
movements predicts a decline,
here's what I can do.

01:09:03.080 --> 01:09:05.340
I'll take some thinly
traded stock.

01:09:05.340 --> 01:09:06.670
I'll get a friend.

01:09:06.670 --> 01:09:09.840
We'll trade back and forth and
we'll influence the price to

01:09:09.840 --> 01:09:11.490
create -- we'll deliberately
create a Head

01:09:11.490 --> 01:09:14.000
and Shoulders pattern.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:17.350
And then we'll short the stock
massively, right at the time

01:09:17.350 --> 01:09:19.060
when the head and shoulders
pattern

01:09:19.060 --> 01:09:21.760
would give a sell signal.

01:09:21.760 --> 01:09:24.710
We can make tons of
money doing that.

01:09:24.710 --> 01:09:26.840
So, why don't we do that?

01:09:26.840 --> 01:09:29.330
Well, we don't because
it's a manipulation.

01:09:29.330 --> 01:09:42.689
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

01:09:42.689 --> 01:09:44.310
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: I
want to then just conclude

01:09:44.310 --> 01:09:48.090
with social contagion, because
it's so important.

01:09:48.090 --> 01:09:49.340
This is my last --

01:09:51.470 --> 01:09:57.625
and this is really social
psychology.

01:09:57.625 --> 01:09:59.930
I'm running out of room here.

01:09:59.930 --> 01:10:01.920
That's social contagion.

01:10:01.920 --> 01:10:06.470
Social psychology reflects on
the fact that people are

01:10:06.470 --> 01:10:09.980
interdependent, and what I
think is affected by what

01:10:09.980 --> 01:10:11.230
others think.

01:10:15.340 --> 01:10:18.360
There's something called
herd behavior.

01:10:18.360 --> 01:10:19.870
That's a popular term.

01:10:19.870 --> 01:10:25.750
It refers to the tendency for
people to move with the herd,

01:10:25.750 --> 01:10:26.720
not consciously.

01:10:26.720 --> 01:10:29.340
They don't think that they're
moving with the herd.

01:10:29.340 --> 01:10:31.990
I might bring up a little
sociology here

01:10:31.990 --> 01:10:34.210
and I'll use a term.

01:10:34.210 --> 01:10:37.490
Everything has been psychology,
but the great

01:10:37.490 --> 01:10:40.790
sociologist, one of the founders
of the discipline of

01:10:40.790 --> 01:10:50.990
sociology, was the French
scholar Emile Durkheim at the

01:10:50.990 --> 01:10:53.140
late 19th, early 20th century.

01:10:53.140 --> 01:11:03.820
And he used the word
''collective consciousness.''

01:11:03.820 --> 01:11:07.450
And that is, that our opinions
about what's happening are

01:11:07.450 --> 01:11:12.180
formed by a collective
understanding of

01:11:12.180 --> 01:11:14.940
what's going on.

01:11:14.940 --> 01:11:20.980
We have a tendency to think of
ourselves as rational and

01:11:20.980 --> 01:11:21.860
common sense --

01:11:21.860 --> 01:11:24.500
all of our views come
from common sense

01:11:24.500 --> 01:11:27.620
processing of facts.

01:11:27.620 --> 01:11:31.140
I have a sense of belief about
what goes on in the world, but

01:11:31.140 --> 01:11:36.700
I underappreciate the extent to
which my views are a little

01:11:36.700 --> 01:11:40.790
bit arbitrary and shared by
millions of other people.

01:11:40.790 --> 01:11:44.710
You live in a certain point in
time in history, and there are

01:11:44.710 --> 01:11:48.450
certain kinds of facts and ideas
and anecdotes that are

01:11:48.450 --> 01:11:50.700
circulating.

01:11:50.700 --> 01:11:56.680
There's another term, this is
a zeitgeist. That's German,

01:11:56.680 --> 01:11:58.500
but it's now English.

01:11:58.500 --> 01:12:01.890
That means "spirit
of the times."

01:12:01.890 --> 01:12:06.020
So, what Durkheim and other
sociologists allowed us to

01:12:06.020 --> 01:12:10.510
understand is, that the
zeitgeist is determined by a

01:12:10.510 --> 01:12:13.310
collective memory, a collective
set of facts that

01:12:13.310 --> 01:12:14.700
we operate on.

01:12:14.700 --> 01:12:19.380
This herd behavior creates big
swings in the stock market and

01:12:19.380 --> 01:12:21.590
other things.

01:12:21.590 --> 01:12:25.050
So, it has a huge financial
impact.

01:12:25.050 --> 01:12:29.190
But anyway, I've listed a number
of Behavioral Finance

01:12:29.190 --> 01:12:31.800
principles that really come
from psychology, and I've

01:12:31.800 --> 01:12:36.370
talked about some tests or
examples of their proof of

01:12:36.370 --> 01:12:40.450
their importance in finance.

01:12:40.450 --> 01:12:42.770
But what do we conclude
from this?

01:12:42.770 --> 01:12:51.930
I think that my conclusion is,
that we are evolving toward

01:12:51.930 --> 01:12:56.620
better and better financial
institutions.

01:12:56.620 --> 01:13:01.150
There is a lot of manipulation
and exploitation, but we as a

01:13:01.150 --> 01:13:03.670
society have outlawed
a lot of it.

01:13:03.670 --> 01:13:08.340
For example, I mentioned doing
a stock market manipulation

01:13:08.340 --> 01:13:11.140
trick to create a Head and
Shoulders pattern.

01:13:11.140 --> 01:13:12.085
That is an offense.

01:13:12.085 --> 01:13:14.590
It will get you in jail
for doing that.

01:13:14.590 --> 01:13:17.100
And we prosecute that now.

01:13:17.100 --> 01:13:19.550
So, you can't do that.

01:13:19.550 --> 01:13:22.160
I'm going to talk more about
this in the next lecture about

01:13:22.160 --> 01:13:23.380
regulation.

01:13:23.380 --> 01:13:26.710
But it's also people's moral
judgments that the people who

01:13:26.710 --> 01:13:30.270
evolve to become important in
finance are people who have an

01:13:30.270 --> 01:13:35.710
internal compass, a desire for
praise-worthiness that

01:13:35.710 --> 01:13:37.510
eliminates --

01:13:37.510 --> 01:13:42.400
I'm going to give just two
examples of some recent

01:13:42.400 --> 01:13:45.250
articles about this.

01:13:45.250 --> 01:13:51.240
In the current issue of the
Harvard Business Review that,

01:13:51.240 --> 01:13:55.170
I assume, is still
on newsstands --

01:13:55.170 --> 01:13:58.210
This is Harvard Business
Review.

01:13:58.210 --> 01:14:05.530
There's an article by Michael
Porter and co-author Mark

01:14:05.530 --> 01:14:11.510
Kramer, Porter is a well-known
professor at Harvard, in which

01:14:11.510 --> 01:14:17.000
he argues that we're coming to
realize more and more about a

01:14:17.000 --> 01:14:21.080
principle called -- he calls it
''shared value.'' Or they

01:14:21.080 --> 01:14:29.390
call it ''shared value.'' And
that is that the manager of a

01:14:29.390 --> 01:14:38.660
company shouldn't be
underestimating the importance

01:14:38.660 --> 01:14:45.520
of shared value creation with
society, with other people.

01:14:45.520 --> 01:14:50.430
That is, we're all in this
together, and if we're mature,

01:14:50.430 --> 01:14:53.760
we recognize, for example,
that I don't want to be

01:14:53.760 --> 01:14:55.160
exploitative.

01:14:55.160 --> 01:14:59.890
I don't want to make the local
people in my town upset with

01:14:59.890 --> 01:15:00.800
our company.

01:15:00.800 --> 01:15:05.040
I don't want our labor force
to become disenchanted.

01:15:05.040 --> 01:15:08.820
Now, what he's saying it's not
really about morals exactly.

01:15:08.820 --> 01:15:11.110
It's more about long-term
value.

01:15:11.110 --> 01:15:15.410
But I guess morals somehow
creeps into the same judgment.

01:15:15.410 --> 01:15:20.670
That mature businesspeople see
shared value and that there

01:15:20.670 --> 01:15:24.610
was maybe not enough
emphasis on that.

01:15:24.610 --> 01:15:28.130
Financial theory was leading
us too much toward thinking

01:15:28.130 --> 01:15:32.930
that a manager should be
selfishly pursuing a narrow

01:15:32.930 --> 01:15:36.030
focus, like maximizing
the short-run

01:15:36.030 --> 01:15:38.610
value of their shares.

01:15:38.610 --> 01:15:43.130
Anyway, the other example I
have, which is also recent,

01:15:43.130 --> 01:15:46.890
not quite as recent as that, is
a book that came out last

01:15:46.890 --> 01:15:52.250
year by Anna Bernasek,
who is actually a

01:15:52.250 --> 01:15:56.920
journalist, not an academic.

01:15:56.920 --> 01:16:01.000
But it's called Economics
of Integrity.

01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:02.250
Is that the title exactly?

01:16:05.270 --> 01:16:06.830
Yes.

01:16:06.830 --> 01:16:08.115
Economics of Integrity.

01:16:12.880 --> 01:16:19.200
And her point in that book is,
that a sense of personal

01:16:19.200 --> 01:16:23.670
integrity has dominated what
people do in the business

01:16:23.670 --> 01:16:28.460
world much more than we
thought recently.

01:16:28.460 --> 01:16:33.290
There has been too much
disregard of the fact that

01:16:33.290 --> 01:16:36.140
people do things because
they're right.

01:16:36.140 --> 01:16:39.050
She gives an example in the book
-- and I'll close with

01:16:39.050 --> 01:16:40.210
this concept.

01:16:40.210 --> 01:16:44.650
She said, let's consider milk.

01:16:44.650 --> 01:16:46.695
Now, you drink milk
regularly, I hope.

01:16:46.695 --> 01:16:48.180
It's good for you.

01:16:48.180 --> 01:16:51.020
But it could poison you.

01:16:51.020 --> 01:16:54.890
People used to get sick from
drinking contaminated milk.

01:16:54.890 --> 01:16:56.930
And you don't ever hear of
anyone getting sick.

01:16:56.930 --> 01:16:58.850
So she said, why is that?

01:16:58.850 --> 01:17:02.590
Well, we have government
regulation of milk production

01:17:02.590 --> 01:17:06.850
and there are laws about
purity of milk.

01:17:06.850 --> 01:17:09.500
But she looked into it
and found that --

01:17:09.500 --> 01:17:13.430
actually, she didn't think it
was mostly the regulation.

01:17:13.430 --> 01:17:18.280
She thought that you are safe
drinking milk because of the

01:17:18.280 --> 01:17:21.330
integrity of our
people, mostly.

01:17:21.330 --> 01:17:24.510
That if you go out to some milk
company and talk to the

01:17:24.510 --> 01:17:28.130
employees, they might not
generally even know about the

01:17:28.130 --> 01:17:29.340
regulations.

